    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_294143996" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/294143996" />
    <a title="Gavin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8192509-gavin"><img alt="Gavin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1338207884p2/8192509.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/294143996?book_show_action=true">Mar 14, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Gavin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Gavin" href="/user/show/8192509-gavin">Gavin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8192509-gavin?shelf=romance">romance</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer294143996" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9756786222031709503">My recent nostalgia trek through favourite books/series of my teen years has finally branched out from the fantasy genre and onto some romance. That made a Judith McNaught book an easy pick as she was the first romance author I read back in the day (thanks to my library mistakenly shelving Night Whispers as a thriller) and to this day she remains the best romance author I&apos;ve read due to the way her books always manage to suck me fully into the story and emotionally engage me with the characters </span>
  <span id="freeText9756786222031709503" style="display:none">My recent nostalgia trek through favourite books/series of my teen years has finally branched out from the fantasy genre and onto some romance. That made a Judith McNaught book an easy pick as she was the first romance author I read back in the day (thanks to my library mistakenly shelving Night Whispers as a thriller) and to this day she remains the best romance author I've read due to the way her books always manage to suck me fully into the story and emotionally engage me with the characters and the happenings. I picked Almost Heaven as it is a book I recalled enjoying a lot. <br /><br />I'm honestly surprised I've not reread this book in the last 8 years since I joined Goodreads. I reread romance favourites more often than books from any other genre and this is definitely one of my favourite romance stories of the lot! <br /><br />How did it hold up nowadays? Pretty well! It was just as good as I remembered it being and for pretty much all the same reasons. I'm pretty indulgent with my favourites from the 80s and 90s and tend to be able to overlook their flaws, even if I spot a lot more of them than I did back in my innocent teen years, but I have to admit that I was happily surprised by how well this story held up. I've read some of my other romance faves in the last decade, including other McNaught books, and outside of the Amanda Quick books I've read I think this is the one that has aged the best. It is still a late 80s written historial romance so has some dated views but it definitely holds up better than a lot of McNaught's earlier books. <br /><br />The story here was a ton of fun. Elizabeth Cameron and Ian Thornton meet at a party during the first few weeks of Elizabeth's first ever season in London and become infatuated with each other over the curse of the evening. A series of mishaps and intrigue ensue which ends in scandal and disaster and the two are separated for a few years until Elizabeth's money grasping uncle comes up with a crazy scheme to try and marry her off to anyone who will have her. Another mishap lands her back in Ian's life and the second time around he finds letting her go is not so easy despite the disaster she brings to his life! <br /><br />It was an enjoyable and engaging tale that was a lot more fun and emotionally engaging than the blurb makes it sound. I quite like a bit of comedy in my romance and this tale had the perfect mix of comedy and drama to keep me amused but also emotionally engaged in the characters and the happenings. It helps that McNaught has always had a talent for writing stories that fully suck me into them from start to finish. I found both Elizabeth and Ian likeable and easy enough to root for as both individuals and as a couple and that always makes it easy to enjoy a romance story. Elizabeth was a pretty typical McNaught heroine (so she was easy to like and root for) but I felt like the big advantage for Almost Heaven was the fact that Ian was more likeable than the average McNaught heroes. He reacted fairly well to all the madness he got caught up in and the same cannot always be said of 80s and 90s romance leads! <br /><br />This was a favourite of my teen years and I was delighted it lived up to those memories and was just as good this time around. It is still one of my favourite romance reads. I just wish I could find more romance books that suck me into the story like this one! <br /><br />Rating: 5 stars. </span>
  <a data-text-id="9756786222031709503" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


